We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) should properly evaluate the completeness of Bidding Documents, Eligibility and Technical requirements and other documents before recommending the award of contracts to the Municipal Mayor in line with the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations;

The Municipal Government shall enter into contract with the winning bidder, provided, that all documentary requirements are complied with;

Management should submit the required documents; and


The Municipal Accountant must require all pertinent documents before certifying the disbursement vouchers as to the completeness of supporting documents in line with Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 to avoid doubts on the legality, validity and propriety of transactions.

We recommended that Management instruct the:
General Services Officer to –
cancel the PARs issued on the small tangible items and issue ICS to the end-users to monitor the said items;
maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE and updated PAR for issuance to end users;
report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the IIRUP duly signed by the Head of Accounting Unit, Inspector/Appraisal Committee and approved by the Local Chief Executive or authorized representative, and submit the report to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition; and
keep the unserviceable PPE in a secure place or warehouse and dispose them immediately.
Municipal Accountant to –
effect the necessary Adjusting Entries to eliminate the small tangible items and their corresponding accumulated depreciation and ensure that future procurement of small tangible items be accounted for in accordance with COA Circular No. 2005-002;
record in the agency books the purchase of the ambulance and consequently provide for its depreciation;
recognize depreciation expenses on PPEs not yet provided with depreciation; and
derecognize unserviceable properties from the books upon disposal thereof based on the approved IIRUP.

We recommended that management:
1. facilitate the completion of the road map to be maintained by the General Services Officer;
2. instruct the GSO and Municipal Accountant to reconcile the local road inventory report and road map with the Accounting records;
3. direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant of the complete description and cost segregation of the road networks; and
4. require the Municipal Accountant to do alternative procedures in determining unrecorded Road Networks like reconciling the accounting records with the roadmap. For the amount to be transferred to the accounting records, the guidelines of COA Circular 2015-008 should be observed.

We recommended that management take the following courses of action:
a) The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) should properly evaluate the completeness of Bidding Documents, Eligibility and Technical requirements and other documents before recommending the award of contracts to the Municipal Mayor in line with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184 and its Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations;
b) The municipal government shall enter into contract with the winning bidder, provided, that all documentary requirements are complied with;
c) Management should submit the required documents; and
d) The Municipal Accountant must require all pertinent documents before certifying the disbursement vouchers as to the completeness of supporting documents in line with Section 4(6) of P.D. 1445 to avoid doubts on the legality, validity and propriety of transactions.

We recommended the management the following:
Instruct General Services Officer- Designate to maintain an efficient property management by following the prescribed procedures in property recording and maintain accurate property records and regularly renew Property Acknowledge Receipt (PAR);
Require Accounting Office to maintain an updated property, plant and equipment ledger cards reconciled with the property cards of the GSO.

We recommended management the following:
Stop the procurement of goods on reimbursement basis, unless the circumstances warrant its application;
Require the department head to submit the Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) of their offices for consolidation into an Annual Procurement Plan (APP) by the Bids and Awards Committee for proper planning and execution of the procurement process so as for them not to resort to reimbursement basis.

We recommended the management the following:
Ensure that all terms and conditions embodied in the contracts entered into by the LGU were all complied by both parties concerned;
Provide a copy of the suspension of work with the disclosure of revised target date of completion of the project;
Properly observe the guidelines embodied in Annex E of the IRR of RA 9184 (Liquidated Damages, Suspension of Work, Extension of Contract Time);
Engineering Department to continuously monitor the on-going infrastructure projects of the LGU to ensure its completion within the target date; and,
Submission of accurate reports as to the status of projects  (PPA).
During the exit conference, management presented various suspension orders to the audit team. In addition, management instructed the Municipal Engineer to conduct thorough inspection on the LGU’s infrastructure project.

We have recommended the Management to ensure that the benefits are delivered to the beneficiaries in an effective and efficient manner by:
Carefully reviewing the PPA’s gender-responsiveness before incorporating it in the Annual GPB of the LGU;
Secure endorsement/approval from DILG Regional Office to  ensure the GPB’s validity;
Full utilization of the GAD Fund in accordance with enacted and DILG-Approved  GPB; and,

Monitor strict implementation of the PPA’s.

